gomodel:SYNGO_3056  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.2: \"\n- \"At later stages of development, when neurons established synapses (DIV14), wild-type Flag-kaptin again colocalized with F-actin-rich sites. Along dendrites, these sites appeared mainly to represent F-actin-rich postsynapses, given that almost all kaptin-enriched puncta were contacted by presynaptic structures containing bassoon (a marker for presynaptic active zones) (Figure 2C).\"\n- \"The vast majority of anti-kaptin-immunolabeled puncta were not only enriched with F-actin but were additionally immunopositive for Shank2, a postsynaptic scaffold protein interacting with F-actin binding proteins;12,13 Figure 2D). \"\n\nNote: I do not think that this data is able to demonstrate localization to the actin cytoskeleton as claimed by the authors. Co-localization observed with confocal microscopy does not mean physical association. However, Kaptin is known to bind F-actin (see Additional literature) which allows for inference to the term 'postsynaptic actin cytoskeleton (GO:0098871)'.. Experimental description: - \"Primary rat hippocampal cultures were prepared and cultured as previously described\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2018-03-29" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_3056" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .
